query = '''

-- create table that groups by year enforced and counts the instances in each year
--filter to active agreements only

with table1 as (select
year_enforced, count(status) as count_enforced
from dyad_level
where status = "active"
group by year_enforced), 


-- create table that groups by year terminated and counts the instances in each year
--filter to terminated agreements only

table2 as (select
year_terminated, count(status) as count_terminated
from dyad_level
where status = "terminated"
group by year_terminated)


-- merge on year and calculate net new as difference between enforced and terminated
-- for years where terminated is NA replace net new with enforced

select a.year_enforced as year, a.count_enforced, b.count_terminated, 
case when b.count_terminated is null then a.count_enforced 
else (a.count_enforced - b.count_terminated) end as net_new
from table1 a left join table2 b on a.year_enforced = b.year_terminated

'''

y = pd.read_sql(query,conn)

query = '''

-- Create table where country A is always not the country of interest
-- Country B is always the country of interest
-- active bits in place = 1 when one of the parties is a country of interest

select distinct country_A, country_B, 
case when country_A in ("China", "United States", "Russia", "Germany") or country_B in ("China", "United States", "Russia", "Germany") then 1 else 0 end as active_BIT_in_place,
case when country_A in ("China", "United States", "Russia", "Germany") then country_B else country_A end as country,
case when country_A in ("China", "United States", "Russia", "Germany") then country_A else country_B end as country2
from dyad_level
where status = "active" and (country_B in ("China", "United States", "Russia", "Germany"))

'''
z = pd.read_sql(query,conn)

Task 3¶

1) In general, countries with higher gdp per capita (such as Germany, Switzerland, and Luxembourg) have have more BITs than countries with lower GDP per capita (such as Somalia and Afghanistan). However, there are some exceptions such as Egypt, Morocco, and Malaysia, which have low GDP per capita but have a higher number of BITs. Regime type may be indicative of this as many of these "exceptions" have a history of monarchies.

2) The 1990s saw a sharp increase in the number of BITs entered into, as compared to the 1980s. This can in part be explained by the creation of new independent states after the dissolution of the soviet union in 1991 and as trade increased and developing countries began signing treaties with each other. In recent years (2000s and 2010s) the number of BITs agreements have been falling. In 2020, net BITs agreements for example, net new treaties were negative. This may in part be explained by the signing of an agreement in 2020 that terminated intra EU agreements.

3) Germany has the largest number of active BITs with other countries, followed by China. This may in part be explained by the fact that both Germany and China have large trade surpluses, and may be more likely to enter into BITs to protect their trade interests. In comparison, the United States has fewer active BITs and has one of the largest trade deficits in the world.
